## Backup Strategy

### The 3-2-1 Rule

\*Three Copies:\* Always maintain at least three copies of your data:

1.  Primary working copy
2.  Local backup (external drive)
3.  Off-site backup (cloud or physical location)

\*Two Different Media Types:\*

- Internal SSD + External HDD
- SD Card + NAS
- Cloud + Physical

\*One Off-Site:\*

- Cloud backup (Backblaze, AWS S3, Google Drive)
- Physical drive at separate location
- Automated sync to remote server

### Field Backup Workflow

\*During Recording:\*

- Use dual-card recording when available
- Copy to laptop during breaks
- Never erase cards until verified backup exists

\*End of Day:\*

- Copy all cards to laptop/portable drive
- Verify copies with checksum validation
- Format cards only after double-verification

\*Checksum Verification:\* ''\`bash

# Generate MD5 checksum

md5sum original_file.wav \> checksum.md5

# Verify copy

md5sum -c checksum.md5 ''\`

## Monitoring Standards

### Reference Levels

\*Calibrated Monitoring:\*

- Calibrate monitors to 85dB SPL with -20dBFS pink noise (film standard)
- Alternative: 79dB SPL for nearfield/smaller rooms
- Use SPL meter at listening position

\*Monitor Selection:\*

- Use full-range monitors or monitors with subwoofer
- Minimum frequency response: 50Hz-20kHz (±3dB)
- Position monitors at ear level, forming equilateral triangle

### Headphone Monitoring

\*Field Recording:\*

- Closed-back headphones for isolation
- High impedance (80Ω+) for better noise rejection
- Extended low frequency response essential

\*Recommended Models:\*

- Sony MDR-7506: Industry standard, detailed mids
- Sennheiser HD 25: Durable, excellent isolation
- Audio-Technica ATH-M50x: Extended bass response
- Beyerdynamic DT 770 Pro: Comfortable for long sessions

## Recording Environment Optimization

### Noise Floor Targets

\*Professional Standards:\*

- Music studio: NC-15 to NC-20 (25-30dB SPL)
- Broadcast studio: NC-20 to NC-25 (30-35dB SPL)
- Voice-over booth: NC-15 or lower
- Field recording: Depends on content, generally \<40dB desired

### Electrical Considerations

\*Power Quality:\*

- Use dedicated circuits for audio equipment
- Avoid sharing circuits with lighting dimmers or motors
- Consider power conditioning for sensitive equipment
- Test outlets for proper grounding

\*Ground Loop Prevention:\*

- Star grounding configuration
- Lift grounds systematically to identify problems
- Use balanced connections wherever possible
- DI boxes with ground lift for instruments

