## Quality Control

### Pre-Delivery Checklist

\*Technical Verification:\*

- \[ \] All files play without errors
- \[ \] No digital clipping (check with waveform analysis)
- \[ \] No dropout or glitches
- \[ \] Correct sample rate and bit depth
- \[ \] Metadata properly embedded
- \[ \] File names follow convention

\*Content Verification:\*

- \[ \] All required takes/scenes captured
- \[ \] Audio matches notes and logs
- \[ \] Quality meets project standards
- \[ \] No missing channels or files

### Listening QC Protocol

1.  \*Full Playback\*: Listen to entire recording at reference level
2.  \*Spot Check\*: Verify critical moments and transitions
3.  \*Technical Analysis\*: Use meters and spectrum analyzers
4.  \*Documentation\*: Note any issues with timestamps

## Delivery Standards

### Common Delivery Formats

\*Broadcast/Film:\*

- Format: Broadcast WAV (BWF)
- Sample Rate: 48kHz
- Bit Depth: 24-bit
- Channels: Poly file or discrete mono files

\*Music Production:\*

- Format: WAV or AIFF
- Sample Rate: Match session (typically 44.1kHz or 48kHz)
- Bit Depth: 24-bit minimum

\*Archival:\*

- Format: BWF or FLAC (lossless)
- Sample Rate: Original recording rate
- Bit Depth: Original recording depth
- Include full metadata

### File Transfer

\*Large File Delivery:\*

- Aspera, Signiant, or MediaShuttle for broadcast
- Frame.io or Dropbox for smaller productions
- Hard drive shipping for massive projects
- Include checksum files for verification

## Conclusion

These best practices represent the accumulated wisdom of professional
audio engineers worldwide. While specific situations may require
adaptation, following these guidelines ensures consistency, reliability,
and quality in your recordings. Regular review and continuous
improvement of your workflows will establish you as a trusted,
professional recordist.

